         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne, ¶ 20/3/87. ¶  ¶ Herewith, honored Sir, I beg to send for your kind acceptance a few lithographic plates, illustrative of W.A. Acacias from an Atlas of these kind of plants, ¶ B87.13.04, B88...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">87.03.20</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To John Brooking</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Acc. 541, AN 3, 271/1887, Surveyor General's Department, State Records Office of Western Australia, Perth.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">20/3/87.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Herewith, honored Sir, I beg to send for your kind acceptance a few lithographic plates, illustrative of W.A. Acacias from an Atlas of these kind of plants,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; margin-left: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B87.13.04, B88.12.01.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>for which about 60 species are already lithographed, and in which the numerous species of your wide territory will also be largely contained. May I ask kindly to find out from flowering and fruiting specimens, whether it is the Acacia heteroclita, which yields about Geographe Bay and Cape Leewin<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Cape Leeuwin? Both WA.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>the peculiar Gum, well known as different from the ordinary Acacia Gum of W.A. I should like to know this for the new edition of my select plants.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M's note on<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Acacia heteroclita</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in the next (1888) edition of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Select extra-tropical plants</seg>… (B88.12.01, p. 7) was unchanged from earlier editions.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Altho Cape Leewin was discovered and named, as you will be aware, already in 1622, the vegetation of the vicinity is even now only imperfectly known.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>For my work on the Australian Acacias my material is also yet very incomplete, particularly as regards the far eastern species, of many of which I have flowering but not fruiting specimens, and until the latter are gradually acquired, they cannot be treated in the Atlas. Indeed collections of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">all sorts</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>of plants even the minutest weeds, rushes, aquatics &amp;c are particularly wanted from your<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">far</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>eastern districts, not so much for actual novelty, but for tracing the distribution of the species. I am thankful for all the aid, already afforded by the survey-department, — and if the eastern settlers would all give a little local help, great strides could be made for completing the elucidation of the W.A. Flora.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am greatly beholden to you for allowing Mr King to furnish me with brief notes on the W.A. surveys of 1886 for my next presidential address;<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>H. S. King. See B87.05.03, p. 31. In B87.04.03, M described the plants collected by King during his survey.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and I feel also much indebted to you for recommending for his Excellency's favorable consideration the joint Exploration by W.A. &amp; S.A. of the country N.W. of Lake Amadeus.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>NT. See M to H. Ranford, 25 January 1887.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Should this not finally be carried out, it would still be a great advantage to W.A., if Mr Giles's<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn5" n="6">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ernest Giles.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>services were secured for one of the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">far inland</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>districts as Crownlands<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Commissioner, as by his connections and influence in the eastern colonies he could speed settlement much<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Is it not a pity, that a Gold-Medallist of the R.G.S. and a leading Australian Explorer should not be in his element again!, one who has done so much for W.A. particularly.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Acacia heteroclita</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
         </div>
